      <hedline>
        <hl1>Napster and Buggies</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Lipson letter says Napster and like companies are not threatening future of music (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I agree with Mike Stoller (''Songs That Won't Be Written,'' Op-Ed, Oct. 7) that songwriters should be paid for their work. But he's wrong when he says that Napster and companies like it are threatening ''the future of music itself.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I agree with Mike Stoller (''Songs That Won't Be Written,'' Op-Ed, Oct. 7) that songwriters should be paid for their work. But he's wrong when he says that Napster and companies like it are threatening ''the future of music itself.''</p>
        <p>The buggy-whip makers might as well have declared that automobiles threatened the future of transportation. None of us have the right to expect that inventions or creations that may have been valuable when new will continue to pay royalties forever.</p>
        <p>Those who depend on the recording industry are doomed unless they and it can find a way to keep pace with the reality of the wired world. Napster is not a culprit. It is a leader that the music industry must learn to follow.</p>
        <p>DAVID LIPSON  Wayne, Pa., Oct. 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
